Quantum-Photonic AI Video Processor

This project proposes a conceptual architecture for a quantum-photonic AI video processor: a hardware system where incoming video streams are encoded into optical impulses and processed through a crystal-based photonic structure rather than through conventional electronic GPU logic alone.

The core idea is to use integrated photonic components—waveguides, beam splitters, phase shifters, resonators, delay lines, and photodetectors—to perform high-speed neural video transformations directly in the optical domain. Instead of storing entire video frames inside the photonic processor, the system accumulates and compares changes across short time windows, such as the 16.7 ms frame interval of a 60 FPS video stream.

The proposed architecture separates three roles: a conventional computer for input and memory, a quantum-photonic crystal processor for optical neural transformation, and an output layer that converts optical results back into a processed video stream or compact change map.

The system is intended for real-time AI video effects, object detection, segmentation, optical flow, enhancement, and potentially generative video transformations. Its advantage is not that light exceeds physical speed limits, but that optical propagation, parallelism, low-loss channels, and physical matrix operations may allow visual information to be transformed with lower latency and reduced heat compared with purely electronic processing.

The concept explores a hybrid architecture where large memory remains electronic, while the most latency-sensitive and parallelizable parts of neural video processing are mapped onto a physical photonic structure.
